               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350706-name-353" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-353" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-353" type="surname" value="BOLTON"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-353" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN BOLTON</persName>
                  </hi>. I live in Charles-square, Moor-lane, Cripplegate. On the 4th of July I saw the prisoner looking in at the prosecutor's window—he went in, and took up something—I gave an alarm, and he dropped these bristles.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18350706-name-354" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-354" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-354" type="surname" value="KNIGHT"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18350706-name-354" type="given" value="MATILDA"></interp>MATILDA KNIGHT</persName>
                  </hi>. I am the daughter of William Knight—he lives in Moor-lane. On the 4th of July, Mr. Bolton told me that the prisoner had got something under his coat—I went and told him to put it down—he took these bristles out of his pocket, or from under his coat, and threw them into the window; he then pushed me off the step—I should have fallen if it had not been for Mr. Bolton.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="italic">Prisoner.</hi> I took some nails out of the box—I did not touth the bristles. <hi rend="italic">Witness.</hi> I am sure he threw them back—I did not see him take them.</p>
